              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11950031197429268660">A historical mystery set in Canada, and featuring what are essentially the precursors to Mounties <i>and</i> gay characters. I <i>really</i> thought I was going to like this book. Instead, I struggled to keep up with its meandering pace and mostly unsympathetic characters, only to be confronted by a conclusion that just cuts out like the end of “I Want You (She’s So Heavy).” I know that sort of thing is supposed to be arty and true-to-life, but is a little bit of closure so much to ask? Several plot threads a</span>
  <span id="freeText11950031197429268660" style="display:none">A historical mystery set in Canada, and featuring what are essentially the precursors to Mounties <i>and</i> gay characters. I <i>really</i> thought I was going to like this book. Instead, I struggled to keep up with its meandering pace and mostly unsympathetic characters, only to be confronted by a conclusion that just cuts out like the end of “I Want You (She’s So Heavy).” I know that sort of thing is supposed to be arty and true-to-life, but is a little bit of closure so much to ask? Several plot threads are completely abandoned, dropped five or ten or fifteen pages from the end and never picked up again. Blargh. Forgive me, but I was reading to find out what happens, not to…I don’t know, muse on how mostly things suck and it’s very cold in Canada.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11950031197429268660" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

