    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2009777503" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2009777503" />
    <a title="Stef Rozitis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31302654-stef-rozitis"><img alt="Stef Rozitis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1528589606p2/31302654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2009777503?book_show_action=true">Nov 21, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stef Rozitis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stef Rozitis" href="/user/show/31302654-stef-rozitis">Stef Rozitis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31302654-stef-rozitis?shelf=historical">historical</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31302654-stef-rozitis?shelf=read-around-the-world">read-around-the-world</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31302654-stef-rozitis?shelf=2001-2010">2001-2010</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31302654-stef-rozitis?shelf=read-women-2017">read-women-2017</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31302654-stef-rozitis?shelf=set-canada">set-canada</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2009777503" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11012039935080360632">This was a very interesting book, sensitively written and complex and managed to have elements of romance in it without putting me off too much (anyone who follows my reviews will be surprised by this). It&apos;s a tad on the bleak and tragic side, although at least it constantly humanises and rehumanises characters.<br/><br/>Two of my gripes were the overall negativity of it (everything has to be shit, fall apart, result in disconnection and loss. All desires must remain unfulfilled). I suppose in some ways t</span>
  <span id="freeText11012039935080360632" style="display:none">This was a very interesting book, sensitively written and complex and managed to have elements of romance in it without putting me off too much (anyone who follows my reviews will be surprised by this). It's a tad on the bleak and tragic side, although at least it constantly humanises and rehumanises characters.<br /><br />Two of my gripes were the overall negativity of it (everything has to be shit, fall apart, result in disconnection and loss. All desires must remain unfulfilled). I suppose in some ways that is better than fluffy positivity, but not everyone will have the stamina to read it and at the end (after persisting so long) I was left feeling vaguely disappointed (less so than with for example "Burial rites" by Hannah Kent but still). I don't like it when the main message of a book seems to be that suffering and disappointment are inevitable and that there is nothing much else to the human condition.<br /><br />The other gripe was that even though there was a sprinkling of strong and relateable female characters, I don't actually think this book passes the Bechdel test. That is it was a book about men relating to men and women relating to men and there was no female relationship developed ANYWHERE in the book, each woman seemed to be an island surrounded only by men or unwilling to reach other to each other. I don't accept this as believable AND I don't enjoy reading it. I'm not saying every book needs to throw in a lesbian romance (though I would enjoy reading that) but something...a friendship, a mother daughter relationship, sisters that actually get along, allies, ANYTHING!<br /><br />I didn't like the constant shifting between first and third person, I have heard it suggested that only having first person from one character can be considered "boring" by some readers. I find it interferes with my "suspended disbelief" to have the shifts in POV this radical and abrupt and I thought that was a weakness in otherwise very strong writing. Perhaps then, there were also too many "main" characters.<br /><br />Ok so I have said what I didn't like. What I did like was the humanity of the diverse characters (male, female, white, "Indian", shifting ethnic boundaries (and other types of boundaries), mad, gay, sexually transgressive etc). The story gave us just enough information without making everything too clear (and it unfolded masterfully). I've critiqued the negativity but I suppose there were traces of hope and meaning within it. Love is a complex thing and connection is difficult. Loyalties shift, people don't fully know themselves. The character of Susannah was a stereotype but I would have wanted to see more of Maria. She is left on the outskirts of the story to some degree.<br /><br />In any case I would recommend this book as a lot better than average. I will read more from Stef Penney (with the fantastic first name) especially if it is more recently written than this. I hope she does more with female characters in future works. Mrs Ross is a damn good start.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11012039935080360632" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


